00:57:17,867 --> 00:57:20,802
That's a start. Get what's
his name back on the phone...

909
00:57:21,004 --> 00:57:24,371
and I'll get this thing booted up
and ready for whatever.

910
00:57:28,745 --> 00:57:29,939
<i>Hello.</i>

911
00:57:30,680 --> 00:57:32,409
So, listen up.

912
00:57:32,615 --> 00:57:35,903
Believe me when I tell you
this whole thing is going south.

913
00:57:35,919 --> 00:57:37,637
So, whatever it is
you were planning to do...

914
00:57:37,654 --> 00:57:39,110
I'd suggest we do it...

915
00:57:39,122 --> 00:57:40,680
and whatever deal
we need to make...

916
00:57:40,690 --> 00:57:42,282
I suggest we make it...

917
00:57:42,292 --> 00:57:45,284
or none of us are going
anywhere or getting anything...

918
00:57:46,362 --> 00:57:49,354
anytime soon, except maybe ten
to twenty in San Quentin.

919
00:57:49,566 --> 00:57:50,658
So, what's it going to be?

920
00:57:50,667 --> 00:57:52,726
<i>Good to hear from you too.</i>

921
00:57:53,069 --> 00:57:55,196
Dude. Shut it.

922
00:57:55,205 --> 00:57:58,891
The police cut the power.
No power, no computer...

923
00:57:58,908 --> 00:58:00,899
no computer, no point.

924
00:58:01,344 --> 00:58:02,936
You count on that little hic-up?

925
00:58:02,946 --> 00:58:06,404
<i>God. Really?</i>
<i>No. I didn't.</i>

926
00:58:07,784 --> 00:58:11,140
Well, you can thank me later.
It's back up for the moment.

927
00:58:11,154 --> 00:58:13,873
Unless you tell me what our little
team here is about to do...

928
00:58:13,890 --> 00:58:16,245
this whole thing's going
to be over before it began.

929
00:58:16,259 --> 00:58:18,591
<i>Is the computer on?</i>

930
00:58:19,028 --> 00:58:19,881
I believe we're good.

931
00:58:19,896 --> 00:58:23,832
<i>Enter that number in the "Personal</i>
<i>Identification Number" sub-menu.</i>

932
00:58:24,200 --> 00:58:28,534
<i>In that page, you'll see four digits</i>
<i>corresponding to an ATM card.</i>

933
00:58:28,872 --> 00:58:30,260
<i>Click that option...</i>

934
00:58:30,273 --> 00:58:33,299
<i>and read me the four digits</i>
<i>that appear in the box.</i>

935
00:58:33,309 --> 00:58:34,970
<i>It is that easy.</i>

936
00:58:35,578 --> 00:58:38,240
- No. It's not.
<i>- I'm sorry?</i>

937
00:58:38,515 --> 00:58:41,006
Last time I checked,
there's no "l" in "team"...

938
00:58:41,017 --> 00:58:44,214
or "felony grand theft
of a federal reserve bank."

939
00:58:45,188 --> 00:58:47,520
You get that number
and you're gone.

940
00:58:49,058 --> 00:58:52,027
That PIN number belongs
to an ATM card I don't have...

941
00:58:52,195 --> 00:58:56,052
which belongs to an account I don't
have. So unless you can find...

942
00:58:56,065 --> 00:58:58,659
a way to share your little
high-tech heist you're stuck.

943
00:58:58,668 --> 00:59:01,956
I suggest you begin by telling
me what we're stealing.

944
00:59:01,971 --> 00:59:03,029
And the clock's ticking.

945
00:59:03,139 --> 00:59:04,868
<i>Okay. Fine.</i>

946
00:59:05,708 --> 00:59:08,609
<i>Nickels and dimes.</i>
<i>Lots of them.</i>

947
00:59:10,079 --> 00:59:12,240
What? Why?
Why are we stealing change?

948
00:59:12,248 --> 00:59:14,216
<i>Why? Because I could.</i>

949
00:59:14,484 --> 00:59:18,318
<i>Getting greedy with what you want</i>
<i>to steal will only get you caught.</i>

950
00:59:18,721 --> 00:59:22,555
<i>You have to ask yourself "why"</i>
<i>you think you can get away with it.</i>

951
00:59:22,892 --> 00:59:27,226
<i>Know "why"and the "what", "where"</i>
<i>and "how" will follow.</i>

952
00:59:27,797 --> 00:59:33,702
Okay, so how are we gonna rob a bank
and actually get away with it?

953
00:59:33,903 --> 00:59:37,737
<i>Ever notice how everything has</i>
<i>some piddly-ass surcharge added?</i>

954
00:59:37,907 --> 00:59:39,534
Yeah. Now you're speaking
to the choir, my friend.

955
00:59:39,542 --> 00:59:42,773
<i>Now I need you to listen closely</i>
<i>and be really honest here.</i>

956
00:59:43,846 --> 00:59:44,631
Shoot.

957
00:59:44,647 --> 00:59:46,911
<i>Do you always balance</i>
<i>your checkbook?</i>

958
00:59:47,083 --> 00:59:50,644
- I've done it.
<i>- Yeah, right.</i>

959
00:59:50,820 --> 00:59:56,110
<i>Even if you do, have you ever checked</i>
<i>to see if a bank didn't charge you...</i>

960
00:59:56,125 --> 00:59:59,014
<i>a surcharge for an ATM transaction?</i>

961
00:59:59,028 --> 01:00:00,154
You had me at checkbook.

962
01:00:00,163 --> 01:00:03,462
<i>Which brings us back to "why."</i>
<i>It's simple.</i>

963
01:00:03,700 --> 01:00:06,692
<i>The world is too complicated</i>
<i>to keep track of.</i>

964
01:00:06,703 --> 01:00:09,490
<i>Life is made of a million moments,</i>
<i>trans actions...</i>

965
01:00:09,505 --> 01:00:12,531
<i>passwords and pin-numbers</i>
<i>to memorize.</i>

966
01:00:12,675 --> 01:00:14,302
<i>It's not that we don't</i>
<i>want to keep track...</i>

967
01:00:14,310 --> 01:00:18,440
<i>it's just that it's not worth</i>
<i>our time until you add it up.</i>

968
01:00:18,615 --> 01:00:21,539
<i>How do we rob a bank and</i>
<i>why will we get away with it?</i>

969
01:00:21,551 --> 01:00:24,987
<i>Add up the chump change.</i>
<i>We're stealing surcharges.</i>

970
01:00:25,388 --> 01:00:28,186
<i>And it's missing money</i>
<i>no one is missing.</i>

971
01:00:29,025 --> 01:00:31,050
What about the bank missing?

972
01:00:31,227 --> 01:00:33,695
- We have a problem.
- Yeah, that's what I said.

973
01:00:33,830 --> 01:00:36,355
No. It's another kind of problem.

974
01:00:39,369 --> 01:00:41,826
I wasn't planning on
getting locked in here.

975
01:00:41,838 --> 01:00:43,692
We've been in here for hours.
I couldn't hold it forever.

976
01:00:43,706 --> 01:00:45,765
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Okay. Of course.

977
01:00:48,044 --> 01:00:49,033
Well.

978
01:00:50,079 --> 01:00:51,478
I just won't look.

979
01:00:55,418 --> 01:00:56,476
All right...

980
01:00:57,854 --> 01:00:59,822
wait, I've got an idea!

981
01:01:00,590 --> 01:01:03,912
- Nick, hold on.
<i>- What's going on?</i>

982
01:01:03,926 --> 01:01:05,359
Don't ask.

983
01:01:08,297 --> 01:01:09,889
What are you doing?

984
01:01:23,780 --> 01:01:25,304
No way!

985
01:01:25,782 --> 01:01:27,682
Beggars can't be choosers, man.

986
01:01:29,786 --> 01:01:30,935
So, what about
the bank noticing?

987
01:01:30,953 --> 01:01:34,514
<i>Okay. Well, like I said,</i>
<i>you never rob the bank...</i>

988
01:01:34,524 --> 01:01:37,152
<i>at least not noticeably.</i>

989
01:01:37,160 --> 01:01:37,990
Stop it...

990
01:01:38,227 --> 01:01:41,424
<i>So, what if, for every dozen</i>
<i>ATM transactions...</i>

991
01:01:41,431 --> 01:01:44,320
<i>you simply divert one surcharge</i>
<i>into an account already set-up...</i>

992
01:01:44,333 --> 01:01:47,461
<i>within the bank.</i>
<i>Nothing more than missing nickels...</i>

993
01:01:47,470 --> 01:01:48,835
<i>and no way to track it.</i>

994
01:01:48,971 --> 01:01:50,689
Yeah. I'm all for
the economics lesson...

995
01:01:50,707 --> 01:01:53,801
but what are we really
talking about here?

996
01:01:53,810 --> 01:01:54,936
<i>Honestly?</i>

997
01:01:54,944 --> 01:01:57,606
This is the only choice you have if
you ever wanna see any of that money?

998
01:01:57,914 --> 01:02:02,044
<i>Okay. Eight million two hundred sixty</i>
<i>six thousand five hundred dollars.</i>

999
01:02:05,822 --> 01:02:07,551
<i>Can you hear me now?</i>

1000
01:02:09,592 --> 01:02:13,153
- That's a lot of transactions!
<i>- Those nickels and dimes add up.</i>

1001
01:02:15,898 --> 01:02:16,956
And no one's on to you?

1002
01:02:16,966 --> 01:02:19,594
<i>Why? The stolen money never</i>
<i>left the bank.</i>

1003
01:02:19,602 --> 01:02:24,539
<i>The irony is, it is all just sitting</i>
<i>in legitimate Grant Liberty accounts.</i>

1004
01:02:25,208 --> 01:02:27,676
- Waiting to be withdrawn.
<i>- That's right.</i>

1005
01:02:28,845 --> 01:02:30,528
As long as you have a valid
PIN number to those accounts...

1006
01:02:30,546 --> 01:02:32,605
you can just slowly withdraw it...

1007
01:02:32,615 --> 01:02:34,970
using nothing more than an ATM card.

1008
01:02:34,984 --> 01:02:38,078
- No one would ever notice!
- How to rob a bank.

1009
01:02:38,755 --> 01:02:40,848
And actually get away with it.

1010
01:02:42,225 --> 01:02:44,375
If I'm not mistaken,
we'd better work out a deal...

1011
01:02:44,393 --> 01:02:46,452
before there's nothing
worth working out.

1012
01:02:46,462 --> 01:02:47,713
So, you give us
your account numbers...

1013
01:02:47,730 --> 01:02:49,686
and we'll assign the PIN
to a new ATM card.

1014
01:02:49,699 --> 01:02:52,088
<i>No deal.</i>
<i>If I just give you the accounts...</i>

1015
01:02:52,101 --> 01:02:54,558
<i>Giving you the accounts</i>
<i>is like giving me the PIN.</i>

1016
01:02:54,570 --> 01:02:57,971
<i>No guarantee the other</i>
<i>won't take off with it all.</i>

1017
01:03:04,180 --> 01:03:07,172
Okay. What now?

1018
01:03:07,450 --> 01:03:10,146
<i>Somebody just has</i>
<i>to trust somebody.</i>

1019
01:03:12,054 --> 01:03:15,387
I don't suppose my good
word would be sufficient?

1020
01:03:16,592 --> 01:03:18,617
Honor among thieves and all that?

1021
01:03:19,195 --> 01:03:20,423
Wait.

1022
01:03:20,997 --> 01:03:22,521
"Insufficient funds."

1023
01:03:22,532 --> 01:03:25,558
That's what got my ass into
all this in the first place.

1024
01:03:26,002 --> 01:03:30,132
- Yeah! Your twenty bucks, surcharges.
- No. My PIN.

1025
01:03:30,339 --> 01:03:33,706
We assign my PIN number
to "Nick's" accounts.

1026
01:03:33,843 --> 01:03:35,162
That way only I know my PIN...

1027
01:03:35,178 --> 01:03:37,373
and only "Nick" has the card
and the accounts.

1028
01:03:37,713 --> 01:03:38,737
<i>And?</i>

1029
01:03:40,249 --> 01:03:43,548
You see, you can't use the
ATM card without my PIN number...

1030
01:03:44,086 --> 01:03:46,850
and without the card and
the accounts, the PIN is useless.

1031
01:03:47,089 --> 01:03:48,511
We don't have to trust each other.

1032
01:03:48,524 --> 01:03:50,116
We can meet and use
the two together...

1033
01:03:50,126 --> 01:03:52,117
and go our separate ways.

1034
01:03:52,361 --> 01:03:53,988
<i>Works for me.</i>

1035
01:03:58,968 --> 01:04:02,597
Just hold on to that idea.
I'd better get this.

1036
01:04:06,776 --> 01:04:07,936
Hello?

1037
01:04:08,177 --> 01:04:10,065
All right the power has been up
for over ten minutes now...

1038
01:04:10,079 --> 01:04:12,502
and still no word
from anybody in there.

1039
01:04:12,515 --> 01:04:16,451
- Have you heard anything?
<i>- Uh, not really, well, you see...</i>

1040
01:04:20,389 --> 01:04:22,414
What? I didn't know what else to do.

1041
01:04:23,426 --> 01:04:25,087
I think we're out of time.

1042
01:04:25,494 --> 01:04:27,621
<i>Hey, what's up?</i>

1043
01:04:28,764 --> 01:04:30,982
This is it. It's now or never.
Either we go with Jinx's plan...

1044
01:04:31,000 --> 01:04:33,286
or that money just sits
in the bank forever.

1045
01:04:33,302 --> 01:04:36,794
<i>Okay, you're right. A couple a million</i>
<i>bucks is better than none, right?</i>

1046
01:04:36,939 --> 01:04:38,224
<i>Just go to the computer...</i>

1047
01:04:38,241 --> 01:04:41,165
<i>do what I told you before</i>
<i>you have Jinx enter his PIN.</i>

1048
01:04:41,177 --> 01:04:42,337
All right.

1049
01:04:56,592 --> 01:04:59,356
Jinx. What is it?

1050
01:05:00,997 --> 01:05:05,696
I don't know. What if we get caught?
What if we end up serving life?

1051
01:05:06,269 --> 01:05:07,600
Life?

1052
01:05:08,571 --> 01:05:09,765
Right.

1053
01:05:10,706 --> 01:05:12,230
See, I don't know about you, Jinx...

1054
01:05:12,241 --> 01:05:14,903
but this hasn't felt like
much of a life to me.

1055
01:05:17,480 --> 01:05:19,641
Just some anonymous hired hand.

1056
01:05:21,550 --> 01:05:25,077
Is this my life?
This for the rest of my life?

1057
01:05:25,621 --> 01:05:28,374
Is your life about
$1.50 surcharges...

1058
01:05:28,391 --> 01:05:31,417
playing bitch-boy to every Simon
and Grant Liberty?

1059
01:05:32,895 --> 01:05:35,295
When are we going to make
some choices of our own?

1060
01:05:40,870 --> 01:05:42,167
Today has been...

1061
01:05:44,674 --> 01:05:45,834
different.

1062
01:05:47,576 --> 01:05:49,237
I think this is it.

1063
01:05:51,013 --> 01:05:56,383
You know, I think this is life.
Choices like this.

1064
01:05:59,355 --> 01:06:04,122
You know, our lives aren't some
big monumental moment.

1065
01:06:06,062 --> 01:06:08,189
It's a choice here,
and a choice there.

1066
01:06:09,632 --> 01:06:12,430
Life is made up like that,
of these tiny moments.

1067
01:06:15,671 --> 01:06:18,435
I think I'm sick of this life.

1068
01:06:21,077 --> 01:06:22,339
So...

1069
01:06:23,346 --> 01:06:26,315
How big can we make
this moment Jinx?

1070
01:06:28,584 --> 01:06:30,415
And get a life.

1071
01:06:32,955 --> 01:06:36,823
Are you insane?
This is a tiny moment to you?

1072
01:06:40,129 --> 01:06:41,323
Yeah. Okay. Yeah.

1073
01:06:41,564 --> 01:06:44,192
It's a big moment.

1074
01:06:44,600 --> 01:06:47,000
It's a... yeah.

1075
01:06:48,170 --> 01:06:51,537
But the principle's the same.
Make a choice. What are we gonna do?

1076
01:06:52,475 --> 01:06:53,965
What are you going to do?

1077
01:06:55,077 --> 01:06:59,275
I'm going to get my twenty bucks...
and then some.

1078
01:07:00,549 --> 01:07:03,143
Right. Yeah.
Let's do this.

1079
01:07:04,820 --> 01:07:06,378
Enter your PIN.

1080
01:07:07,857 --> 01:07:10,155
So, this little box is the key
to our fortune, huh?

1081
01:07:13,562 --> 01:07:17,293
There. That's it.
We're done. Now what?

1082
01:07:21,170 --> 01:07:24,037
Now, we go.

1083
01:07:26,942 --> 01:07:30,969
<i>Excuse me... guys? It just occurred</i>
<i>to me. We have a problem.</i>

1084
01:07:31,213 --> 01:07:34,512
- What's up?
<i>- Well, you have no way out.</i>

1085
01:07:35,684 --> 01:07:40,519
- What?
<i>- Well, she doesn't have a way out.</i>

1086
01:07:43,159 --> 01:07:45,445
What do you mean? She's got
the scam with the cops.

1087
01:07:45,461 --> 01:07:47,315
They think she's one of the hostages.

1088
01:07:47,329 --> 01:07:50,924
<i>Okay, well, that doesn't solve</i>
<i>the "Simon problem."</i>

1089
01:07:51,667 --> 01:07:54,192
<i>Even if you wait until</i>
<i>the cops storm the place...</i>

1090
01:07:54,203 --> 01:07:55,795
<i>he's not going quietly.</i>

1091
01:07:55,805 --> 01:07:59,673
<i>He can easily turn her in when he</i>
<i>finds out she's not busted with him.</i>

1092
01:08:00,543 --> 01:08:03,808
No, no. Not after all this.

1093
01:08:10,753 --> 01:08:11,845
Hold on.

1094
01:08:17,026 --> 01:08:18,584
Officer DeGepse here.

1095
01:08:18,594 --> 01:08:21,279
<i>I'm sorry my signal died,</i>
<i>but I'm back in a good zone.</i>

1096
01:08:21,297 --> 01:08:23,265
Great, any news?

1097
01:08:23,866 --> 01:08:26,050
<i>Simon says he appreciates</i>
<i>your show of good faith...</i>

1098
01:08:26,068 --> 01:08:28,764
<i>and in return, he's willing</i>
<i>to release two hostages.</i>

1099
01:08:31,807 --> 01:08:34,867
- Me and Jessica.
<i>- No shit? Really?</i>

1100
01:08:35,377 --> 01:08:37,641
<i>Okay, okay, we got you covered.</i>

1101
01:08:38,080 --> 01:08:43,108
We got you covered. Look.
Okay, look. Listen...

1102
01:08:43,119 --> 01:08:46,520
make your way out slowly
and we'll take care of the rest.

1103
01:08:47,323 --> 01:08:49,291
This will all be over soon.

1104
01:08:49,425 --> 01:08:52,121
So, I'll tell Simon you're ready
for the release.

1105
01:08:54,396 --> 01:08:56,421
Now, we're cooking with gasoline.

1106
01:08:57,633 --> 01:09:01,125
- Do you have any way of reaching Simon?
- Yeah, I can call Roger.

1107
01:09:01,504 --> 01:09:04,473
- Who?
- His muscle.

1108
01:09:04,807 --> 01:09:05,831
The other guy on the team.

1109
01:09:05,841 --> 01:09:07,968
He gave me his number in case
there were complications.

1110
01:09:08,110 --> 01:09:10,078
I think this qualifies
as a complication.

1111
01:09:10,212 --> 01:09:11,873
Nick, we're gonna call you back.

1112
01:09:15,818 --> 01:09:17,445
<i>- Hello?</i>
- I gotta talk to Simon.

1113
01:09:17,453 --> 01:09:19,444
<i>He's kinda busy at the moment.</i>
<i>Who is this?</i>

1114
01:09:19,455 --> 01:09:21,423
Roger, put him on the phone.

1115
01:09:31,967 --> 01:09:33,992
- Hello?
<i>- Hey, it's me, Jinx.</i>

1116
01:09:34,503 --> 01:09:36,528
Hey Jinx, what's up?

1117
01:09:38,107 --> 01:09:41,201
I have to admit
you've really got me worried now.

1118
01:09:42,711 --> 01:09:44,872
<i>Sorry for the wait,</i>
<i>but we better make a deal fast.</i>

1119
01:09:44,880 --> 01:09:47,269
<i>- I got off the phone with DeGepse.</i>
- What did he say?

1120
01:09:47,283 --> 01:09:50,002
<i>He says that if they don't see</i>
<i>cooperation from you within 5 minutes...</i>

1121
01:09:50,019 --> 01:09:51,805
<i>they are storming</i>
<i>the place with SWAT.</i>

1122
01:09:51,820 --> 01:09:53,185
Shit! Shit...

1123
